It was a very special experience for me.
As I completed the Pradakshina and faced the deities again, it felt like a piece of puzzle had fallen into place.
I could never have asked for more on this Diwali.
I could have easily spent this day sulking over the distance and all the fun I could have had at home.
But finally it dawned on me today that miles don't matter, but the people do...
It felt like looking into the pensieve, just like Dumbledore did.
A long lost memory had decided to screen itself before my mind.
I think the moral of the story is very much implicit...
One of the games I used to play with kids in the building was, climbing the ladder on the terrace that led to the water tank.
It was more of an activity than a game.
The water tank was the highest point on top of our 4 storey building.
After playing for some time, we kids would sit on a level each of the ladder staring up at the sky or observing the terraces around us.
The ladder must have been about 15 to 20 feet tall, I fail to recollect its exact length because to me, climbing that ladder was way out of my league.
I was expressly forbidden to go beyond the first four rungs of the ladder.
"It is too dangerous.
You will fall."
Those words just echoed in my mind every time I went close to the ladder.
So I ended up being the one sitting at the lowest level.
When summer came, one of my playmates climbed way till the top and sat down on the water tank.
I was awestruck.
Two others used to climb it half way up and stand on a support like beam that used to connect the ladder to the wall of the water tank.
That was some feat too.
For days that ladder continued to entice me.
It was partially peer pressure, but I always wanted to climb all the way to the water tank.
One day, I mustered a lot of courage and reached that support beam.
I was half way up the ladder, I was thrilled!
To look at the tiny streets winding their way from between the many buildings.
To watch the activities in other terraces -someone putting out clothes on the line, someone playing hopscotch, red chilies being spread out on a carpet - it was a fantastic feeling.
That level became a bench mark.
Now when I looked up at the sky, nothing came in the way, all I could see was the wide blue sky, with its fluffy clouds floating along silently across the horizon.
It was bliss.
Like, all good things, this feeling wasn't going to last long.
I started longing to see what it would feel like from the very top.
However, when it reached my home that I have been climbing the forbidden ladder, I had to face some music.
The same words were freshly embossed into my mind.
I was told that I should not be seen in the vicinity of that ladder anymore.
I could use the first four rungs if I really wanted to sit on the ladder.
Well, it was no fun sitting on the lowest rungs, now that I knew how it felt like to sit half way up the ladder.
I still mused about the top of the water tank.
But whenever I looked up at it, a sense of foreboding gripped my heart.
It seemed totally unattainable.
Finally, I gave up, "It was too dangerous, I would fall."
Something yucky but funny happened just as I arrived at my desk.
Yesterday I had observed a piece of cardboard lying below the desk beside my dustbin.
It seemed odd and out of place and I thought it was something my neighbor had left.
Today when I came, I saw the same cardboard still lying there untouched.
I was a little annoyed to think that no one bothered to pick it up and throw it away.
Now, I had spread out my umbrella for drying beside my chair.
To conserve space I decided I should put the umbrella below the desk.
So I moved one dustbin aside and then when I touched my foot to the cardboard to move it as well….
SPLOCHHH….
something gooey had stuck to my foot.
For about 2 whole minutes I could not understand what had happened.
Then I realized it was some sort of a glue.
When I looked closely, there was something written on the cardboard, "TRUBBLE GLUE".
What an apt name!
Now, a thought came to my mind - Was this a trick?
But I disregarded that thought because this doesn't seem to be a place where people play pranks on each other.
The next 10mins I was busy wiping my foot on the carpet.
I was afraid if I wore my shoe I would be stuck with it (pun intended) for quite some time.
With the help of a tissue and some water I wiped of any residue.
I tried to suppress loud giggles, because this seemed something completely out of the blue to be happening to me.
Finally, when it seemed like most of the glue had come off I dared to wear my shoe.
As I finally settled down, I gave the cardboard another look.
Now the fine print jumped at me - the better rat trap.
Well, that explained the presence of that cardboard under my desk.
A lot of questions buzzed in my mind that very instant.
Why do they need a rat trap on the 6th floor, for instance.
But the most perplexing question was - Why was I barefoot when I touched that cardboard?
