But what about the content?
The evening provided me with just that.
My friend and I went to his place.
An Indian settled in the States isn't very rare these days.
But, an Indian with an American wife settled in the States about forty years ago, is definitely not common.
I really had nothing in mind about the conversations we would have at their place.
I didn't have to try too hard for it either.
"I hope it isn't mandatory to enter through the front door.", he said with a laugh.
The house was typically american, with a large garden and lawn and a garage.
We entered through the backdoor - american style - and came across an american kitchen, with multiple platforms and a large refrigerator overloaded with family photographs.
I tried catching glimpses of their family in the snaps, but could hardly tell who's who.
She greeted us with a warm smile.
A tall figure with moderately stylish white hair and a loving face.
She had prepared dinner - oh no - supper and we were going to have it in the open.
Wow.
There was a table set and as he and my friend started taking things out to place on the table, I handed over the box of homemade indian sweets I had brought with me to her.
I wasn't sure of her reaction but to my relief and wonder she thanked me and recognised them immediately.
I took an instant liking to her.
The food she had prepared was splendid and what made it more delicious were the talks we had while we ate.
They asked us about our course and our lives in India and in the States.
I was fascinated to see the awed expression on her face when I explained to her about the social networking website and how I came to know of my friends through the site.
When it came to laptops she was just as impressed to hear about the advancements of technology and how it was now possible for parents to see their kids though they are miles away.
I zealously explained to her about how net savvy we were and how it had made our lives easier and at the same time how dependent we were on the same.
Her interest was the fuel for my advocacy.
We went inside for dessert when the most amazing part of the evening was about to take place.
She asked me when was the first time I started interacting with computers.
I proudly told her that we had a subject - Computers - when I was in second grade.
I also told her how we learned so many programming languages in school and how because of my father I had a PC at the age of 9.
She listened patiently, smiling.
My friend too, told her about her own experiences with computers.
Then she looked at her husband and told him how things have changed and how there was a time when they had to enter data into the computers using punchcards!
I froze.
Punchcards?
Really?
Then the two of them started discussing about what is the root or the first generation of computers.
How laborious it was to merely put a simple input and how terrible if something went wrong because then you would have to do it all over again.
I felt invisible goosebumps popping up on my skin.
Here I was sitting with users of the first generation computer!
It wasn't just amazing, it was downright unthinkable for me.
And what was I doing bragging about my laptop and how the Internet made life easier?
There were more interesting topics that followed, constituting of changes in technology and how it has affected people and children.
I had such a wonderful time, something I had never predicted.
This experience of being with an American family was something I could have never dreamed of like.
The level of topics that were discussed were so intellectual that it brought me down to ground zero, woke me up and made me open my eyes to the purpose of my visit here.
"There would be no more invitations, you can come in whenever you like." he said as we started to leave.
The goodbye was reluctant from my side because it really felt like I had finally found a home away from home.
