With rush and TP joining us, we had a wonderful time.
The good old days of our team seemed to be back.
Endless jibes and PJs had us laughing till our sides hurt.
Back at my desk I completed the formalities.
Before I realized it was time for the farewell ceremony.
I didn't get a chance to say much at the farewell.. thanks to the rain.
By the time it was my exit interview, it was pretty late.
I said a final good bye to all my colleagues with a heavy heart, it was not at all evident on my face I am sure :P On my way back home on the train, I heaved a sigh of relief, at least no more traveling on a crowded local!
My final words lingered still in my mind, mocking me in a way, I know I didn't give my 100%...
Well so I am back after a long time, there was something that kept me busy, shall write about it later.
Right now, what I really want to narrate is a funny incident that occurred today.
It happened just a few hours back it's really making me laugh still.
Here goes...
So, it's not really unusual for a development craving developer to be sulking while on her way to work on a MONDAY!
Well, after dragging myself through the crowded BEST, trying hard not to push the aunty who was comfortably leaning her handbag and a good proportion of her body on me, I continued across the slippery bridge, and down the murky stairs to the muddy platform where 2 local trains awaited me.
I got onto one of them still moaning over my state, cursing the crowd and the bags and the hair clips and the newspapers and the occasional pointed heels that would nastily stamp my quivering feet.
When I stationed myself behind a lanky lady, I noticed a saree clad woman with her back towards me.
The saree was clearly cheap and I was irritated at these women traveling by the first class.
I thought of speaking out to that woman when she turned around and revealed a man-like face complete with a partial mustache.
I was still for a moment and then realized it was eunuch, a not very uncommon sight in the locals these days, but what the hell was he/she/it doing on the train at such an unearthly hour.
For a second, I was glad I didn't try to rebuke it as planned.
The train set off and it was an uncomfortable journey because the eunuch continuously fidgeted with it's saree.
It would have seemed stupid but it was annoying, I had to keep on shifting uneasily to avoid its touch.
I tightened my grip on my bag, because these people are often thieves.
The next station came and I was hoping it would get down.
When the station arrived, people jumped in but it didn't get down.
There was a chaos thanks to the confusion of these women who were not sure how to react to it's presence in an overcrowded train.
Well, everyone ignored and continued to squeeze in not paying much attention to it.
All serious faces running late for work.
It was when the station after that arrived, that the eunuch faced trouble.
A really huge woman (huge women generally don't give a damn whom they are suffocating to death on a train) got in.
There was a terrible mob and amidst the women screaming at each other to make space in the already jam-packed coach, everyone heard a loud shriek -
"hai hai mujhe aise mat dabao!!!!"
Oh my god, the eunuch was yelling on top of its voice, in that typical nasal tone.
There was silence for a fraction of a second, before everyone in that crowded coach burst out laughing.
The whole situation seemed so funny.
I felt pity for that eunuch who surely regretted getting onto the first class ladies coach on prime time!
How true this wise adage is! Silence is Golden, and considering that nothing else is compared to diamonds or platinum or hot shares or anything else more valuable, people love to adopt this.
Oh yes, they worship silence.
These masses.
This general public.
The common man.
I really wonder why anyone pities the common man or his woes, for I have realized that what he has beget is really what he deserves.
Monday, late evening, 9:10pm.
The worst time one would want to be in a bus queue.
But there I was without an option, shifting my weight from one foot to the other, ignoring the clucking of those equally annoyed at having to wait for a bus for so long.
I notice out of the corner of an eye, another queue taking form beside the one I am standing in.
No one says a word.
There are 4-5 people in the new queue, everyone ignores them.
A minute passes the 4-5 people transform into 10-12 people.
I lose my temper, point it out to those standing before me.
"Why are those people standing in a separate line?",
I exclaim.
"It seems they don't know where the line is.", a boy standing ahead of me answers me.
As if I didn't know that.
"Why doesn't anyone ask them to go behind?
They 'll disrupt the line", I retort, the volume and pitch of my voice slowly hinting my temperament.
A lady standing behind me, makes a move, she motions to ask those people to move back.
Another girl says a few lines.
Still, there is no reaction from the crowd ahead.
"When the bus comes these people standing ahead will cause commotion.
There 'll be a chaos for no reason.
Ask them to go back.",
I yelled at no one in particular, wondering if people were really that deaf.
A man comes and joins the newly formed queue.
"Eh, hello!
Go back!
This is not the right queue!
All these people are not standing in the queue!",
I almost scream at him.
The man pays no heed.
"Hello! Can't anyone hear?
Have these people ahead lost their tongues?
Why can't they tell them to go back?",
I continue ranting.
I had lost the last of my tolerance.
No one uttered a word.
The lady who seemed to be supporting me is quiet.
Suddenly, I feel like a clown, yelling for no reason in particular.
The bus arrives.
As expected there is a scuffle.
The people up ahead push and shove like animals to get inside the bus.
I get a thrust from a man's shoulder on my head.
Finally, I settle into a seat by the window, fuming at the mass.
Yes, they would keep quiet.
Even if a someone hits an old man in the bus, they would keep quiet.
Even if the wrong person takes the chair, they would keep quiet.
Even if they see an open murder, they would keep quiet.
I used to think the movies exaggerate things at times.
But now, I am having second thoughts.
Yes, Silence is the God for these masses.
They worship it, practice it, and use it when they are not in trouble themselves.
